    "abstract": "<jats:p>What drives the dynamics of top wealth inequality? To answer this question, I propose an accounting framework that decomposes the growth of the share of aggregate wealth owned by a top percentile into three terms: a \n            <jats:italic>within</jats:italic> term, which is the average wealth growth of individuals initially in the top percentile relative to the economy; a \n            <jats:italic>between</jats:italic> term, which accounts for individuals entering and exiting the top percentile due to changes in their relative wealth rankings; and a \n            <jats:italic>demography</jats:italic> term, which accounts for individuals entering or exiting the top percentile due to death and population growth. I obtain closed\u2010form expressions for each term in a wide range of random growth models. Evidence from the \n            <jats:italic>Forbes</jats:italic> 400 list suggests that the between term accounts for half of the recent rise in top wealth inequality.\n          </jats:p>",
